From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ondrej Jirman <megi@xff.cz>
Date: Sun, 15 Mar 2026 17:23:59 +0100
Subject: usb: gadget: Fix net_device lifecycle with device_move

Apply the same net_device lifecycle fix from f_ncm (commit ec35c196965)
to all other USB ethernet gadget function drivers that share the same
problematic pattern.

The issue: the network device outlives its parent gadget device during
disconnection, resulting in dangling sysfs links and null pointer
dereference problems. The boolean 'bound' flag cannot properly track
multiple bind/unbind cycles.

The fix replaces 'bool bound' with 'int bind_count' in all ethernet
function opts structures (f_ecm_opts, f_eem_opts, f_gether_opts,
f_rndis_opts) and applies the device_move reparenting pattern:

  - On first bind (bind_count == 0): either register the net device
    (first time ever) or re-attach it to the gadget via
    gether_attach_gadget() (subsequent cycles).

  - On last unbind (bind_count reaches 0): call gether_detach_gadget()
    to reparent the net device to /sys/devices/virtual/.

  - In free_inst: use device_is_registered() instead of the old 'bound'
    boolean to decide between gether_cleanup() and free_netdev().

For f_rndis specifically, the borrowed_net case (used by legacy composite
drivers like g_ether, g_ffs, g_multi) is handled by skipping
attach/detach when the net device is borrowed from another function.

Legacy composite gadget drivers (ether.c, g_ffs.c, multi.c) are updated
to set bind_count = 1 instead of bound = true when they pre-register
the shared network device.

Signed-off-by: Ondrej Jirman <megi@xff.cz>
